Visualizing Educational Attainment in NYC with Dot-Density Map

Alex Henoumont

Abstract

Dot density map is a useful tool for businesses, governments and community leaders to describe populations over time. By collecting data from the American Community Survey, the attributes of the populations can be plotted onto the map and help decide where products and services will produce the greatest benefits. Below describes the process of creating a dot density map to describe the distribution of educational attainment in New York City.

From the map below we see that areas with the highest educational attainment are within Manhattan (below Harlem), Downtown Brooklyn and Williamsburg. Generally educational attainment appears to diminish as distance increases from these areas. It is also worth noting that the Lower East Side has lower educational attainment that its adjacent neighborhoods.

Education in NYC

Dot-Density Map

A dot-density map uses a dot to represent the presence of a feature by creating a scatter to show a spatial pattern. In the example bellow data collected from the American Community Survey (ACS) will be represented by randomly plotting a dot for every 100 individuals within a block group who shares similar educational attainment.

Data Acquisition

American Community Survey (ACS)

The ACS helps local businesses government, and community leaders understand the changes in the population over time. Whereas the US Census’s main objective is to gain an accurate count of the population, the ACS tracks the details such as commuting behaviors, age, heath insurance. The ACS reports 1 and 5 year estimates, depending on wheter currency or relibility is more important to the analysis. For small population sizes (less than 65,000), the 5 year estimate is recomended.To learn more visit [Census Reporter] (https//censusreporter.org/)
This notebook will use the 5 year estimate (2012-2016) to visualize the distribution of educational attainment of citizens 25 within New York City. The observations will be aggregated by block group (600-3,000 individuals) where dots represent 100 individuals with similar educational attainment randomly scattered within the block group. Although the placement is random, block groups are relatively small therefore dots will be fairly close to actual locations.

NYC education by tract from the 2016 5yr American Community Survey

Data Manipulation

The educational attainment is retrieved from table ‘B15003’, however, the ACS has coded 25 levels of educational attainment, B15003_001 through B15003_025. Our next step should aggregate the data into four groups, ‘No HS diploma’, ‘HS, no Bachelors’, and ‘Post-Bachelors’. - ‘B15003_001’ is ommited as it contains the estimated total population for that area. - ‘B15003_002’‘-’‘through ’B15003_016’ includes observations without HS diplomas; - ‘B15003_17’ through ‘B15003_21’ includes HS diploma and no Bachelors degree; - ‘B15003_22’ includes Bachelors degree; and - ‘B15003_23’ through ’B15003_025 includes post-Bachelors degree.

Education <- Education %>%
  mutate(id = str_extract(variable, "[0-9]{3}$") %>% as.integer) %>%
  # variable 1 is the "total", which is just the sum of the others
  filter(id > 1) %>%
  mutate(education =case_when(
    id %>% between(2, 16) ~ "No HS diploma",
    id %>% between(17, 21) ~ "HS, no Bachelors",
    id == 22 ~ "Bachelors",
    id > 22 ~ "Post-Bachelors"
  )) %>% 
  group_by(GEOID, education) %>% 
  summarise(estimate = sum(estimate))

Generating the dots

The dot density plot works by randomly generating dots within the geographic boundaries of the block groups.First the observations will be split by education level, Next, a fuction is defines to sample the observations. To prevent excessive overplotting and minimize computation, each dot will represent 100 individuals. This function with then be iterated over each educational level resulting in four layers, corresponding to each level of education.

# Generate dots, create a group column, and group by group column
split <- Education %>%
  filter(estimate > 0) %>% 
  split(.$education)

generate_samples <- function(data) 
  suppressMessages(st_sample(data, size = round(data$estimate / 100)))

dots <- map(split, generate_samples)
dots <- imap(dots, 
               ~st_sf(data_frame(education = rep(.y, length(.x))),
                      geometry = .x))
dots <- do.call(rbind, dots)

dots <- dots %>% group_by(education) %>% summarise()
dots <- dots %>%
  mutate(education = factor(
    education,
    levels = c("No HS diploma", "HS, no Bachelors",
               "Bachelors", "Post-Bachelors")))
# view how many dots are in each layer
dots %>% mutate(n_dots = map_int(geometry, nrow))

Building the base map

This visualisation will be created by stacking layers on top of each other. This step will retrieve boundary, roads and water layers to help orient the reader to places on the map.

#Get Map Features
#Roads
roads <- rbind_tigris(
  lapply(county, function(x) roads(state = state, county = x))
)
# Filter the NYC  roads object for major roads only
roads <- roads %>% 
    filter(RTTYP %in% c("I", "S", "U"))

# Get an area water dataset for NYC
water <- rbind_tigris(
  lapply(county, function(x) area_water(state = state, county = x))
)


# Get the boundary of DC
boundary <- rbind_tigris(
  lapply(county, function(x) county_subdivisions(state = state, county = x, cb = TRUE))
)

#Check the base map
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = boundary, color = NA, fill = "white")+
  geom_sf(data = water, color = "lightblue", fill = "lightblue") +
  geom_sf(data = roads, color = "grey")

Compiling the layers together

Now that all the layers have been collected, they must be stacked together. 1. Empty layer is first created as a placeholder, 2. Next the boundary is created with a white background, 3. Then the dots are populated, trasparency is added to account for overplotting, and the color of the dats is differentiated by educational level, 4. The water is next added to prevent the posibility of a dot accidentaly plotted over water. 5. Finally the major roadways are added to help with orienting the reader to local neighborhoods and other landmarks.

nyc_education <- ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = boundary, color = NA, fill = "white")+
  geom_sf(data = dots, aes(color = education, fill = education), size = 0.1, alpha = 0.6)+
  geom_sf(data = water, color = "lightblue", fill = "lightblue") +
  geom_sf(data = roads, color = "grey") +
  scale_color_brewer(type = "div", palette = 4) + 
  scale_fill_brewer(type = "div", palette = 4) +
  # geom_sf(data = dots, aes(color = education, fill=education), size = 0.5) +
  coord_sf(crs = 26918, datum = NA) +
  # scale_color_brewer(type = "div", palette = 4) + 
  # scale_fill_brewer(type = "div", palette = 4)+
  labs(title = "Education Attainment in New York City",
       subtitle = "2012-2016 American Community Survey",
       fill = "",
       caption = "1 dot = approximately 100 people.\nData acquired with the R tidycensus and tigris packages.")+
  guides(color=F)
